Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

I want to study social work. I will work for the Division of Family and Children Services. I will help children who were abused or neglected. I will also support troubled families. My values are: service, respect, and ethical behavior. I want to help others and improve relationships. I want to stay good at my job.

I did not know what career to choose. In high school and college, I saw people run away from their problems. Some used bad ways to cope. I thought about it and decided to study psychology. After college, I did not know what to do. I visited a friend. She had a 16-year-old boy with her. He was scared because his parents were abusive. The next day, I went to his parents' house. The police were there. I told them I had a degree in psychology. The parents were nervous. They said their son was "manipulative." This made me think about social work. I could help families with small problems.

Social justice is important. Society says individuals are unique. But we often try to be like everyone else. I don't like limits. In high school and college, I protested against unfair things. I wore bright hair, unusual clothes, and had piercings. I joined GSBA and fought against racism. I will always fight for social justice.

This paper talks about two models for insomnia: biological and sociocultural. The biological model looks at genes and health. The sociocultural model looks at how the environment affects race, ethnicity, and money.

The review looks at these models and explains how research can help explain them. It also talks about the strengths and weaknesses of each study.

A sleep disorder can be a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder caused by another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder caused by other problems. Primary sleep disorders are called Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Dyssomnias are problems with sleeping or staying awake. Parasomnias are sleep disorders that cause strange things while sleeping.

This review focuses on insomnia and some other primary sleep disorders. The biological model of sleep disorders talks about genes and how they affect sleep. Neurons in the brain control sleep. A study with mice found that a special receptor helps sleep. If this receptor doesn't work right, people might have sleep problems. The sociocultural model talks about how sleep problems can affect school, work, and everyday life.

This paper talks about three things about Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a simple explanation. Next, it tells how to find out if someone has CAPD. Finally, it gives suggestions for teachers to help a student with CAPD in a normal classroom.

CAPD is a problem with how the brain processes sounds we hear. People with CAPD can hear normally, but their brain has trouble separating words or hearing conversations. The disorder was first called "auditory imperception" in the 1950s. Researchers found out more about it over time.

CAPD can cause many problems. People with CAPD might not be able to:
- Hear or find where sounds come from,
- Tell the difference between sounds,
- Recognize sound patterns,
- Understand changes in speech,
- Hear one sound over another,
- Use sound clues to understand,
- Follow the order of sounds.

To find out if someone has CAPD, they must take tests and answer questions. No one test is always right, and no one knows why this happens. Many tests use sounds to see how well someone can understand them.

In Twelfth Night, disguise can help trick people, but it is not good in the end. A person must stop being deceptive or lose their true self. This can make people feel alone. People might not like being tricked. In Twelfth Night, Viola becomes a man to protect herself. She feels safe this way. However, she cannot talk to women. Olivia thinks Viola is a man and loves her. Viola wants Orsino, but he loves her as a man. This is confusing. Shakespeare shows that deception can bring out hidden feelings. Olivia loves Cesario but does not love a woman. She likes Sebastian more. She thinks Cesario is like a sister. This shows she does not judge based on looks.

German rule was very bad in South West Africa. Many people were killed. The German colonies had different rules. In East Africa, the government helped Africans learn. In South West Africa, only missionaries taught Africans. The government helped more Europeans than Africans. Many Africans did not learn to read or write. This paper will talk about why this happened.

Many old books about German colonies are in German. They talk about schools in these colonies. New books in English compare schools in different colonies. Cohen’s book talks about schools in South West Africa and East Africa. He says that many people in South West Africa made the schools different.

South West Africa was not as hot as other colonies. Many Europeans lived there. By 1913, there were 15,000 Europeans in South West Africa. This is more than in any other colony.

Popular music has many types, and it is hard to list all of them. Many types have many smaller types. One type, heavy metal, is very different and has many types too. It started 40 years ago. It has many emotions, mostly dark. It also has many rules. People can make their own types and smaller types. Today, it is hard to say what heavy metal is. It started with a boom of drugs in the 70s. People made songs with them. It is not like other music, which is usually happy. Metal has dark words and music. It is like the dark music from the Romantic Era. Old songs like "Helter Skelter" show this. It is dark and heavy.

Henri Rousseau was painting his dreams decades before Surrealists. The Dream, his 1910 painting, shows a woman dreaming. It also shows Rousseau's dreams and goals. He wanted recognition, acceptance, and praise from artists and art lovers. This was his struggle: follow rules or be unique.

To understand The Dream, you need to know Rousseau's story. He was born in Laval, France. His father was a tinsmith. He worked for France until age 40 as a toll collector. He lost his first wife and eight children. He started painting for comfort.

Rousseau wanted art world acceptance. He was untrained and started late. Other artists were successful too. Matisse was a competitor. They were different. Matisse feared painting badly. Rousseau wanted conventional art to be accepted.

Many great thinkers connect ethics and beauty. I think there is a reason for this. John Keats says, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty.” We learn many things in life from school or experience. But we also like good things without learning them in these ways. Both ethics and beauty help us understand, not give rules. We talk about why something is good or beautiful, not how to make good things. People can't fully explain why something is good or beautiful. A person might say, “There's just something about it” when asked about a favorite art or book. I think art and morals have a special, hard-to-explain part. This makes them connected. Kant says, “Ethics cannot be explained. It is something extra, beyond.” I think this special part is the strongest part of both. It is what makes art and morals powerful. We feel art and morals deeply, but can't explain it. This is true for literature too. McKean says, “Literature is unique because of its moral quality. It is important because it shows us values.” So, I think art and morals are closely linked because we feel them deeply. This feeling connects them.

Today's Germany is strong and united. Its culture comes from many places. It can be felt from Munich in the Alps to Kiel by the Baltic Sea. It is also found in Cologne by the Rhine, in the center, and in Dresden by the Elbe. Germany has different origins and tribes.

Germany is the home of the Germans. People do not know where the name comes from. Some say it is from a tribe called Tungrians. Others say it is from a Gaulish word. Some say it is from a spear or a word meaning loud.

A Roman historian named Tacitus wrote about the Germans in 98 AD. He said they are native to the land. He asked why anyone would leave Asia or Africa to go to Germany. He said it is a wild place with bad weather and bad people.

In the first century, German tribes appeared near the Roman Empire. They traded goods and fought in the Roman army. The Romans did not live there. They sent their soldiers to the land and went back home.

Looking down, I saw a bowl of fruit. I did not understand it. I felt nothing. I did not think. My mind only saw the bowl. I wanted to learn to draw since I was six years old. I bought a book called "Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain". This book teaches how to draw. It teaches what pens are and how the brain sees lines. The book says to look at a picture with a square frame. This makes the picture simple. I tried this with the bowl of fruit. I could not see it as a simple square. I was too surprised. I thought about famous artists. I wanted to draw. My hand touched the pen. I had a thought. I saw water in the toilet. Then, I saw the brown package. I flushed the toilet. It did not go away. I saw the package as a message. I used toilet paper to cover it. I was quiet and calm. I used the paper to make a glove. I stood up. I dipped my hand into the toilet like a mother cooking turkey.

Teenagers die in car accidents. Many reasons cause this problem. The teen brain is not ready for driving dangers. Teens lack driving experience. This causes more accidents, road rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. Teens are unsafe with friends. A study shows that more accidents happen with young passengers.

States help teen drivers with temporary licenses. These licenses limit driving hours and ban other teens as passengers. But these licenses are not enough. Teens are not ready for driving risks. A psychologist says 18 is too young to drive. USA Today reports that teens under 19-20 like to take risks. It's better to delay driving until this changes.

Many new teen drivers will be on the road by 2010. We need to protect them. Schools can teach driving, but no one under 18 should drive. A permit should be issued first, and practical driving hours should be required. This is not a new idea.

I found many early Edison films at the Library of Congress. I watched all fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use creative editing to make illusions. I studied the way the films are made. Most films use a stage-like view. The camera does not move. Actors only move side-to-side. The film's length is short, about one minute or less. Most films show tricks, like magic or disappearing acts. Some films use more than one shot to make tricks. For example, "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900) shows actors moving back and forth. The camera does not follow them. The films show long or medium shots, not close-ups. This is like watching a play on stage.

John Taylor from Caroline was a strong Republican early on. He was a farmer. He also worked in politics. He cared deeply about freedom and government. His farming helped him think about these things.

Taylor believed the United States could create a perfect system. There were no old traditions to stop it. He thought people have natural rights. These rights depend on each other. If one is taken away, others are less valuable. The government should not take these rights.

He wanted a government that understands good and bad in people. He thought government must protect private property and farming. He believed good government is important. Even if leaders are not good, a good system works.

Taylor wanted the Constitution to be followed exactly. The Federal government should have only the powers listed. He knew a large government can be bad. He thought the Declaration of Independence is the real guide. It says the country is a group of states, not one nation.

In Figure 17, commuter log submissions fell sharply in the third month. This was disappointing. We do not know why. Winter and the end of the semester might explain some of it. People do not commute by bike or on foot in winter. Everyone is busy finishing schoolwork in December. The commuter log may have been forgotten. December also has holidays. Many do not need to come to campus. Classes start again in January. This may explain the low numbers. The project may also lose momentum over time. We created the Carpool Challenge Week in March to increase participation. This helped. A challenge is to keep people interested in the project, especially during holidays and semester breaks. People like driving their cars. This is part of our culture. We need to give good reasons to use other ways to commute. We gave many prizes, like gift cards. It is interesting to see if bigger prizes, like a nice bicycle or car, would help. We could have added bigger prizes later in the project. Gift cards were good at the start. But, if we announced bigger prizes later, more people might have joined.

An ETF is like a stock on an exchange. It follows an index, commodity, or group of assets. ETFs give you the benefits of index funds and single stock ownership. You can sell short, buy on margin, and buy just one share. ETFs are cheaper to own than mutual funds, but you pay a trade fee. There are many ETFs to choose from. We will look at ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings.

We will check if owning ETF IHF is better than owning the top 10 stocks. We will compare Beta and return. The top 10 holdings make up 63.58% of the ETF. The holdings and their percentages are:

1. Stock A: 30%
2. Stock B: 15%
3. Stock C: 10%
4. Stock D: 5%
5. Stock E: 5%
6. Stock F: 3%
7. Stock G: 2%
8. Stock H: 2%
9. Stock I: 1%
10. Stock J: 1%

We will calculate the Beta and return of a portfolio made up of these 10 stocks. The chart shows that the return of this portfolio is 16% higher than the ETF's return, and the Beta is 12% lower. This means a portfolio of the top 10 stocks could give better returns and less risk. However, we need to check if these differences are big enough to matter.

To check this, we will look at the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks. We will compare it to the ETF IHF's standard deviation.

"Dream-Land" is one of Edgar Allan Poe's best poems. In this poem, he uses "Thulé" twice. This word comes from Virgil's work. Virgil used it to talk about an island north of Britain. Although this is true, Poe might also know it from another author. Poe liked German writers.

This is important because it shows Poe read Goethe's work. Karl J. Arndt said Poe's poem is like Goethe's "Mignon." This means Poe might have copied parts of it.

Goethe's work includes a poem called "The King of Thulé." In this poem, a king loses his wife and becomes very sad. He then drinks a lot and dies. This is like the king in "Dream-Land." Poe might have seen this parallel.

Poe uses "Thulé" twice in his other poems. He also used it in "The Pit and the Pendulum." "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be read together. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about a dark, lonely place and sees ghosts. This is like the feelings in "The King of Thulé."

Goethe was a famous writer. Poe might have known him because he liked Tennyson. Tennyson admired Goethe. This meant Poe would have seen Goethe's work in many places.

In California, can a customer who slipped and fell on applesauce in a grocery store get punitive damages? The judge will likely not quickly throw out Jennifer Palmer's claim. To get punitive damages, the lawyer must show that the store manager acted badly. Palmer can argue that Martin knew the spill could harm people, as many customers had slipped before. Martin did not clean it for a half-hour because he was eating dinner. This was very bad. Six people slipped and fell in the store in 2009, but Martin still did not keep the store safe. On October 13, 2009, an employee told Martin about the spill. Martin said he was on break and did not want to deal with it. Another employee also told him. At 5:30 pm, Palmer slipped and hurt her back. Before Palmer's accident, five people slipped and fell at D&D stores in 2009. Palmer is now suing for damages. We are thinking about filing a motion to stop the punitive damages part of the case. California law says that if a person acts with "oppression, fraud, or malice," they can be punished. The law says that malice means acting to cause harm or doing something very bad with no regard for others' safety. Courts say that conduct is malicious when the person knows it can cause harm and still chooses to do it.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC. We talked about if Islam is a bad religion. This question is still important. Since 9/11, how people talk about Islam has changed. In 2001, it was not possible to have a president with a Muslim name like Barack Obama.

The book about the Prophet Muhammad is interesting. It says Muhammad was a kind man. But history says he forced people to become Muslim. The book says people became Muslim because they saw the truth. This is not true. The book also says Muhammad did miracles like Jesus. This makes Muhammad seem like Jesus. This is bad because it takes away from Jesus.

The book has many stories. These stories say people believed in Islam by themselves. But the stories are not true. They are told by people who heard from others. This makes the stories less believable.

What bothers me most is the book makes Muhammad seem like a good man. History says he was not. If Muslims know the truth about Muhammad, they will not think he was a good man.

Jesus' teachings and beliefs were not kept the same after his life. Over time, Christianity changed and moved away from its start. Today, many people see Christianity growing and changing. Old people stay with old ideas, but they may not be many. In the future, more Christians will learn about history and want to follow Jesus' true ideas, not extra things added later. This will make Christianity return to its beginning. It will take time, but it will happen. When this change happens in the United States and Europe, people will follow Jesus' ideas again. The church will lead, but there will be more agreement in beliefs. History shows big changes. For example, Christians were once hated by the Roman Empire, but it later became Christian. Also, African-American leadership changed from slavery. The Christian change will follow this pattern, undoing history to find the start and making beliefs more similar. Reading Jesus' words as metaphors, not literal, will help this happen. Since Jesus' time, only Judaism existed. It was the start of Christianity. Romans ruled Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish people had different beliefs, like Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and common people.

People in The Jungle are greedy and only think about themselves. They do not care about others. This is shown in many ways. Factory owners and managers only want to make their companies big and rich. They do not care about pollution or workers. Sinclair shows this with the factories' smoke and animal waste. They do not care about workers' safety or how much they work. There were no laws to protect workers. This let managers and owners make workers work fast and in bad conditions. Many workers died from these conditions. There were no help for workers. Unions did not help much. Workers were treated like slaves and had no way to leave.

Many writers use different ways to make readers feel certain things. Some ways are better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses these techniques in his book The Great Gatsby. He often uses words that do not usually fit together. He also gives meaning to things like colors and uses them to make readers feel something.

Fitzgerald builds meaning for colors like white, gray, red, and pink. In his book, he uses white and gray a lot at the start. He uses white for nice, important people. Gray is for old, less important things. People like Daisy and Jordan wear white all the time. Even Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party.

Fitzgerald uses white and gray to show unimportance or sameness. He uses Daisy as an example. After a long time without using these colors, he describes Daisy as wearing white. This makes Daisy seem less important, just something Gatsby wants. He uses this technique to show Daisy like a uniform addition.

San Diego County is good for growing many things because it is warm and sunny. Common crops are tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, fruit like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. Many people buy organic food here. Many farms also offer tours and places for hiking and birdwatching. This can help the farmer make money and help the environment.

Organic farming can make the land better for plants and animals because it does not use chemicals. It can also help make money, but it needs more work. It can also help many animals, but it needs more money and time to do it right. So, the farmer might need help to make the land better for people and animals.

The land in this story is in Potrero, near Cleveland National Forest. It is 160 acres of chaparral, grassland, and oak wood. Many plants and animals live there. Some are rare or disappearing, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog. This area has been used by Native Americans and ranchers for a long time. The farmer wants to use it to grow things and make money without harming the animals and plants.

The farmer looked at different ways to get help from the government. The farmer also looked at what a real organic farm in the area does to make money and help the environment.

Culture is important in negotiation. Culture is like a group of things. It is not one thing. It is not the same in every place. People say things like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are nice." These are not true. A negotiator should understand how a culture affects talks. It is better to study a culture's history and understand its beliefs. It is not good to judge or change a culture. A negotiator should accept a culture and work within its rules, especially if he is new to it. A negotiator should respect traditions and beliefs. A company has its own culture, too. It can be different from other companies. A company's culture can affect how it treats employees and does business. It is important to understand a culture's values. These values tell us why people do things. For example, in some cultures, it is important to save face. So, a negotiator would not publicly shame a company or a superior. In other cultures, people want to make a hard bargain. This affects how they negotiate. It is good to learn about the other negotiator to make the negotiation better.

St. Anselm and St. Thomas Aquinas both believe in God. Their arguments for God's existence are different. We will compare their arguments. We must assume they both believe in the same God for a fair comparison. We will first look at St. Anselm's argument. He thinks God's existence is inside our minds. We can know God by thinking about truth in our own souls. This is called faith. This is different from St. Thomas Aquinas' argument. He thinks God's existence can be proven by reason and evidence. He has five arguments. First, things change. Second, everything has a cause. Third, some things are necessary. Fourth, we compare excellence. Fifth, everything has a purpose. Each argument shows God's existence is logical.

Long ago, a prince was born who became Buddha. He left his world and became wise. His teachings started Buddhism. Today, it looks different. In Sri Lanka, people do a water-cutting ceremony. Buddha did not teach this. Theravada Buddhism has changed over time. This is because of forces inside and outside the religion. We will use special words: internal for Buddhist forces, external for non-Buddhist forces, hostile for forces that harm Buddhism, and benign for forces that do not harm or help.

Theravada Buddhism has core beliefs. Buddhists follow the triple gem: Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. Dhamma is Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka has all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka has rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has metaphysical ideas. Key ideas are Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). By understanding these, one can end Sansara (death and rebirth cycle) and end lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life, like five precepts for laymen and many rules for monks. The four noble truths are: life is suffering, attachment causes suffering, suffering can be overcome.

America and Mexico had a long fight for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The worst fight was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848. America won and took Texas and the American Southwest. Other fights also happened, and they stopped before World War One. The fight started because Americans and Mexicans had different beliefs, traditions, and interests. Other nations also have fights with neighbors. The United States and Mexico are not alone. They had a long, ongoing fight with each other. David Pletcher says, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can you see long-lasting problems between America and these countries" (p. 41). Mexico and Cuba are close to America, and they have been rivals. Other Latin American countries have good relations with America. Religious differences caused problems between America and Mexico. Sally Frahm says, "In the 20th century, Americans opposed fascism and communism. In the 18th and 19th centuries, they opposed Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). The fight was not just about politics but about religion. The Americans and Mexicans did not trust each other because of differences between the British and Spanish. These feelings made it hard for them to be friendly. Diehl and Goerts say there were 17 fights between Mexico and America in those 57 years. Most of these fights were about land and border problems. Bandits and outlaws caused many problems. This changed when Mexico became dependent on America. Finally, American goals changed from taking land to helping Mexico's economy in the late 1800s.

Fifteen years ago, I became very sick. I did not know it would happen. I was a nurse. I chose this job because it made me feel safe and secure. People told me, "You will always have work. People will always need help." So, even though I wanted to be a scientist or journalist, I became a nurse.

Now, I am 46 years old and cannot work. I have no money or things that are mine. Every day is very hard. My family and friends help me. If there was no help, I could not live.

Life has big problems and little problems. Sometimes, things are too big to face alone. We need to help each other and ask for help.

We should not just rely on the big government. It is not good. But we should learn to trust each other and ask for help. In the past, our country was built with kindness, respect, and sharing.

Prepare for emergencies. Have a disaster kit, first aid, water, and food supplies. Know your neighbors. They can help you too.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there rules that make them change in certain ways? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said that even today, scientists can't describe simple things with math. But now, math is used to study how some things change. Our study looks at how math and experiments can help us understand how Prunum shells change. We use X-ray pictures to find numbers for our math. We use these numbers in a computer program to make pictures of shells. We also look at real shells and experiments to understand big changes in this group of animals.

A shell is like a tube that turns around. These turns are called whorls. They go around a central line called the columella. The speed of the turns can be different. The biggest turn is the last one. The top of the shell is called the apex and the bottom is called the base. The animal lives in the shell through a hole called the aperture.

We can look at shells in different ways. We can see the top, bottom, or side. The usual way is to see the side with the aperture facing us and the apex pointing up.

To count how many turns a shell has, we look at it from the top. We draw a line where the first turn starts. We count the turns from this line, estimating a quarter turn if needed.

A shell is like a series of openings that move through time and space as the animal grows. We can follow this path with numbers. Once we have math for the path, we can change numbers to see how the shell changes.

Indonesia has not improved neonatal and infant death rates much in the last ten years. The country is close to meeting some Millennium Development Goals, like water and sanitation targets, but not child and maternal health. This is a problem. The reasons for this are discussed below. The need is to make the health system stronger, not just focus on specific programs.

Indonesia has improved the number of births with a skilled worker. 72% of births have a skilled worker. However, this includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot handle complicated pregnancies. This is why many mothers die from bleeding problems.

Indonesia has also treated fewer diarrheal cases in children under five. This is a concern. Data on postnatal care is unclear, but it is also a problem.

Cesarian-section rates are very low. They are 4% overall. They are higher in cities (7%) and much lower in rural areas (2%). This shows that healthcare is mainly in cities. Also, the poor use healthcare less. They cannot afford it.

The next step to improve neonatal and maternal care is to think about how to deal with the lack of services. Should Indonesia focus on specific programs or make the whole health system stronger? Program-specific approaches have clear goals and can work quickly. However, they can make other areas suffer. They can also cause duplication and more paperwork.

Victorian books often focus on important details and the wealthy people of the time. Two books, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They have strange and unusual stories, which make characters seem more real. In Oliver Twist, these strange things often show what Oliver feels inside. When Oliver is shot, he feels the pain again, like it's a dream. He can't control what happens. He feels sad. He is not strong enough to help himself. This shows that he can't control his life. In the novel, the long night feels both long and short. It is long because it is quiet and scary. It is short because it goes quickly.

Two years ago, I helped children after school. I helped students in any subject they struggled with. My strength was English and reading. One boy, Adrian, needed help. He was in third or fourth grade. He had trouble reading. Some letters he knew, others he did not. He spoke perfect English but had trouble with the alphabet. We struggled until I met his mother. She only spoke Spanish. With my little Spanish, we talked. Adrian could read but did not know the English alphabet well. This helped him. I tell this story to talk about language problems in schools, especially in California. Even a boy who speaks English well can have reading problems. The solution is not simple. It can be tutoring, dual language systems, or other ideas. We need to try all these things together.

For the dual language system, it is good for all children. Children learn better in two languages. Many people think it wastes resources. But if we use it more, all children can learn better. We do not need all teachers to be bilingual. But we can have helpers who speak both languages.

People tell us from young that there is something big, bigger than us, that we can’t understand. Some go to church, temple, or search inside themselves for answers. Some follow what their parents believe, others reject it. We choose a way to find part of ourselves. We look for light in dark, to find bright, happy times.

My father said his favorite bird is a cardinal. We sat on our porch, listening to rain. He was not as strong. His hair was less. He looked out, thinking about past. I felt alone, afraid, and couldn’t talk to him. I hugged him, sat close. He looked out more.

My father died in December, five days after my birthday. His sickness stayed longer than doctors thought. I didn’t want to see him die. I wanted to remember him by how he lived. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for news.

No one called me.

The "Gothic Novel" is an "old-new" mix. It is both old and new. Some people say it has no real depth. Others praise it for its "terrible sublime" feelings. The first Gothic novel is "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole. It uses old and new ideas to make a new type of story. Walpole uses old theater and new nature styles in his story. The word "gothic" was used to describe many things. It was seen as old and not modern. The mix of old and new Gothic helps it last a long time. It becomes both old and new to readers far from the time it was written.

One big idea in Gothic novels is Chivalry. Chivalry is the old idea of training a knight. In "The Castle of Otranto," this idea is kept and changed. Chivalry is important because it represents a brave, honorable knight. Walpole, when he wrote, was in a bad political time. He might have thought good people from the past were gone in the present. In his story, a character named Frederic shows this. The reader sees Frederic as a prince who has suffered and is brave. He is like a "gallant and courteous Knight," but also shows the new Gothic idea of excess.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from order to customer. This process includes planning, doing, and controlling how goods move. The term "supply chain management" was made by Keith Oliver in 1982. It is about making sure customers get what they want quickly and well.

There are six main parts to a supply chain: making goods (production), getting materials, keeping goods (inventory), choosing where to do things (location), moving goods (transportation), and sharing information.

Managers use these parts to give good service to customers.

Making goods is the first step. It is important for the whole supply chain. Managers need to know what customers want and when. They look at the market to find out. After knowing what customers want, managers decide what to make and how much. They also decide where to make it and which plant is best. After that, they plan when to do things and take care of equipment. Everything must be planned well to save time and money.

The second key part is getting materials. This is about making good decisions to get the right skills and partners. A company may have many places to make a product. Each place has different equipment and workers. The manager decides which place is best for each part of the product. They may also choose to get help from other companies. This helps to do things quickly and well, while keeping costs low.

Sign says: Hitler alive in Burma.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone with a sign on the street. The sign has a message in Burma, also called Myanmar. Myanmar is a country in Southeast Asia. A group called a junta rules it. They took power in 1962. In 2007, many people protested. Monks led the protests. They wanted to change the government. This is called the Saffron Revolution. At first, the government let the monks meet. But then, more people joined. The government fought back. They hurt a Japanese photographer named Kenji Nagai. Many people say more people died than the official count. A military colonel said many more people were killed. This is not new. Many governments have done bad things to stop people from protesting.

The Roman emperors thought they were gods. They controlled people. Japanese emperors are believed to be gods. George W. Bush talks to Ted Haggard each week. Haggard is the leader of a group called Stupid People Worldwide.

Many people know about bad things governments have done. In 1989, people in China protested at Tiananmen Square. Some say 2,000 people died. In 1994, many people were killed in Rwanda. In the 1930s and 1940s, Hitler's government killed many Jews.

Duke Ellington's music is famous because he played for a long time and wrote great songs. He was a good piano player. He wrote songs that show the talents of his band members. He liked when band members played alone and improvised. He also wrote songs with many instruments playing together. Many of his songs are famous because they sound unique. The Grove Music Dictionary says Ellington used voice as a special instrument. In Creole Love Call, a song from 1927, he used voice to add special sounds. There are six parts in this song. In each part, different instruments take turns playing the melody. Other parts have the whole band playing together. In Hot and Bothered, a song from 1929, Ellington used a special sound from a trumpet player and a singer. He also used a trombone player to play a special sound in It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing). All these songs show that Ellington's music has a special sound.

She always felt like she needed something. This feeling started when she was 14. It is still there now, at 17. She wants someone, not a thing. She is not interested in boys, even though some boys try to be friends. She does not know why. She thinks about this often. She lives, feeling confused.

A day at home is usually peaceful. Her parents are good. They do not argue. They are calm. She is also calm. She is independent and free. She is nice.

Today, something happened. She heard a scream. She ran to the kitchen. Her mother was in pain. She helped her mother. Her mother asked her to go to the hospital. She drove her mother there. The hospital smelled of sickness. She felt worried. Doctors took her mother. Her mother fell from a stool.

This study looked at whether following the Mediterranean Diet (Med diet) might help prevent heart disease and stroke. It used a special diet called the alternate Mediterranean diet (aMed diet). This diet has more plants, including fruits, nuts, and whole grains, and less animal products. It also has more monounsaturated fat and less saturated fat. Some alcohol is allowed.

Before, other studies showed that the Med diet might help reduce death from heart disease and other problems. But they didn't look at stroke or stroke deaths.

This study followed 74,886 women from 1984 to 2004. They were in the Nurses' Health Study. They reported their food intake six times. More than 95% stayed in the study for 20 years. Reports of heart disease and stroke were checked with medical records. Results were adjusted for many things that could affect the results.

The study used a special math called Cox proportional-hazard modeling. It showed that women who ate more like the Med diet had less heart disease and stroke. In 20 years, there were 2,391 heart disease events, 1,763 strokes, and 1,077 deaths from heart disease or strokes. Women who ate more like the Med diet had less risk of both heart disease and stroke.

In 2007, America had a big financial problem. It was called a recession. People lost their jobs, houses were hard to sell, and many big companies were in trouble. This problem is still happening today. So, how did it happen, and how can we stop it in the future?

The financial crisis started when banks and companies made bad decisions. They gave out loans to people who could not pay back. The government company, Fannie Mae, and Freddie Mac, helped with these loans. When people did not pay, the banks had no money to help. This made other parts of the economy very bad.

The problem started in 1999, when the president wanted to stay in power. He made it easier for people to get loans. A news article said this could cause problems. The article was right. The economy got worse because of the bad loans.

Many things made the economy worse. One was the way mortgages were made. People got loans that changed with time. This made the economy depend on the housing market too much. When the housing market went bad, the whole economy got worse.

The big banks had a lot of debts from these loans. In 2007, they had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts. This was a big part of the USA's economy. Some big banks were sold or shut down. Fannie and Freddie were also in a lot of debt. They were put under government control in 2008.

Exposition is the part in your story where you introduce background information. It can be good or bad. Sometimes, it can keep readers interested. Other times, it can make them bored or confused.

We know the writing tip, "Show, don't tell." But Dr. Merlin still sometimes writes too much. She writes long passages where nothing happens. Or she writes too much detail.

Exposition means telling the audience what happened in simple words. In a movie, exposition is when one character tells another about something important. In a story, the author does the telling.

Example: Suppose a heroine meets her husband. The story says they met, got married, and he was killed in front of her. But you wouldn't expect this to take two pages with only a few lines of dialogue. You'd expect the author to show how the husband loved his wife, and how her life changed because of him. This would make you care about his death and understand the heroine better.

So, you need to give details. You can't just say "They met, they married, he died." You need to show the story's bones with some meat.

I watched two news shows from Columbus, Ohio. The first was a live show from NBC 4 on August 13, 2011. The main story was about a man named Shad Hostettler. He stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. They showed his picture. They said he was arrested. They spent about two minutes on this story.

The second story was about a shooting in Sharon Woods. Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old man, was critically injured. No arrests were made. The SWAT team is investigating. This story seemed short. I think it might be because he is black.

The next story was about a gunshot hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. It happened in a certain place. A .22 caliber rifle bullet hit it. Crime-Stoppers offers a reward for information.

Another story was about rain and thunderstorms for Saturday afternoon. The temperatures will be in the mid to low eighties.

The next story was about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF store. A dark-skinned black man robbed it. He was about six feet tall and weighed about 150 pounds. I think they spent too much time saying he was black.

The last story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin. He was convicted of selling marijuana in Ohio. They said he was Hispanic. They said he was sentenced to 300 months in prison. I don’t understand why they said that instead of 25 years.

Brothers have a strong bond. This bond is like no other. It has many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and anger. Brothers know each other well. They see themselves in each other. When times are hard, this bond shows. It shows good or bad feelings. These feelings bring trouble. Understanding these feelings is hard. It means knowing the bad things that happen. When a brother looks at another brother, he sees himself. He sees his true self, not how others see him. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers talk about this bond. They go on a long trip. They have many feelings. They feel proud and disappointed. One brother dies. This shows the bond. The story is about feelings. It's about how a brother, Doodle, feels. The other brother, the narrator, shows his feelings too. His feelings make him act.

The narrator feels angry. He wants a brother who can do things. He wants to teach him. He wants to race and climb trees. Doodle can't do these things. He is weak. He has a weak heart. He can't be like the narrator. The narrator is sad. He wants to hurt Doodle. He thinks about killing him. But he loves Doodle. His brother's smile makes him love him. The narrator's love is strong.

The brain is a complex system. Technology changes from simple to modern, so do brain descriptions. At first, it was called like a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and now a computer. Remember, these metaphors are not always right.

Information processing starts with senses. They turn physical things into signals that the brain uses. There are two types of brain processing: bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up uses simple data like color and shape to decide what you see. Top-down helps you understand what you see faster. For example, you might see a black box on a white background.

After processing, the brain chooses which information to focus on. This is called attention. You might not notice grass, but you hear your name. There are many stages of processing, and attention changes the results.

The brain needs to store information. There are different types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Sensory memory stores short-term info. Working memory stores info for about 20 seconds. Long-term memory stores info for a long time.

There are many ways to understand how the brain stores information. Some use how people remember, some use computers, and some use brain science. The semantic network model says that information is stored in nodes that are linked based on how they relate to each other. For example, "chair" might be linked to "table" and "wooden".

Aldous Huxley criticizes future dangers from technology and the capitalistic system in his novel Brave New World. People here like community more than themselves. They learn from birth to want happiness. They are like pieces on a chessboard, controlled by the World Controller. The story shows the author's worries about these systems. Many words from Marxism, like homogeneity and reification, show this. The story talks about the problems in the economy from Huxley's time.

The novel uses the Marxist idea of false consciousness to show how people are controlled. Workers do not know their true position. They are interested only in their own gain. They are taught to want to spend and consume. This is like the World Controller controlling them. Hegemony shows how the lower classes do not know they are controlled. The upper classes know but do not act. Most Alphas and Betas accept their place. Interactions between classes show the power of capitalism.

People in Brave New World do not have real relationships. Characters do not have depth. Maybe Huxley says this to show how technology and capitalism take away free will. Love and strong emotions do not exist. People talk about women's bodies and their nights together. They are happy with their place in society. This is like Marx's idea of the proletariat. They think they are better if they consume and obey.

I have been a student at University Park for nearly three years or more than four semesters. Getting around campus can be hard for many students, including me. First year, I lived in East Halls, far from the center. Walking to classes in places like Willard building could take 25 minutes or more, especially in bad weather. Today, that area has new buildings and sports fields. As the campus grows, it becomes harder to move around. What is the best solution? Bicycles.
I talked to a friend. He said, “Bikes are good. They are the best way to move around.” Bikes are good for your body and are more efficient than walking. They can take you far. I live off campus, near the center. I bought a bike this year. It takes 5 minutes to ride to Thomas building, compared to 25 minutes walking. The problem is, Pollock Road is not easy. If I didn't have a bike, walking would be my only option. That would add 30-40 minutes to my day. So, I need a better way to travel.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
